President Muhammadu Buhari yesterday returned to Abuja from the capital of Cote d’Ivoire, Abidjan, where he attended a Summit of Head of States and Government of the 15th session of the Conference of the Parties (COP15) of the United Nations Convention to Combat Desertification (UNCCD). Buhari, who departed Abuja on Sunday and returned at about 6:10pm yesterday, delivered update on Nigeria’s environmental efforts to the summit, which had the theme: ‘Land. Life. Legacy: From scarcity to prosperity’.   ‘Malabu scam’: Defendant voluntarily gave statement, says…     Aviation fuel not selling at N700 per litre, says MOMAN     ‘Airline operators trying to force govt to introduce…   The COP-15 was a United Nations- organised conference on the future of land, regarding desertification, drought, degradation, rights, restoration and implications for national and world economies. Buhari, who is also the President of the Great Green Wall in Africa, was accompanied on the trip by the Minister of Foreign Affairs, Geoffrey Onyeama; Minister of Environment, Mohammed H. Abdullahi; Minister of Agriculture, Dr. Mahmoud Mohammed and Minister of Water Resources, Suleiman H. Adamu, an engineer. Also on the President’s team to Abidjan were the National Security Adviser, Maj. Gen. Mohammed Monguno; Director General, National Intelligence Agency, Ambassador Ahmed Rufai Abubakar and Chairman/CEO, Nigerians in Diaspora Commission, Abike Dabiri- Erewa.